{"title_page": "Broadford, County Limerick", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Brawwford\n| other_name                      = {{pad top italic|B\u00e9al an \u00c1tha}}\n| settlement_type                 = Town\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_caption                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = Ireland\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Ireland\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Munster]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[County Limerick]]\n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"census2016\">{{cite web|url = http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ST2016&Geog_Code=C8875475-766E-451D-8E48-5C736DDBEA94 | title = Census 2016 - SAPMAP Area - Settlements - Broadford | publisher = CSO | work = Census 2016 | date = 2016 | accessdate = 19 August 2018}}</ref>\n| population_total                = \n| population                      = 276\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| timezone1                       = [[West European Time|WET]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +0\n| timezone1_DST                   = [[Irish Standard Time|IST]] ([[Western European Summer Time|WEST]])\n| utc_offset1_DST                 = -1\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|52.3450991|-8.9740563|dim:100000_region:IE|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| blank_name                      = [[Irish grid reference system|Irish Grid Reference]]\n| blank_info                      = {{iem4ibx|R350220}}\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Broadford''' ({{Irish place name|\u00c1th Leathan}} - \"Wide Ford\") is located in the west of [[County Limerick]] in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It is part of the [[Roman Catholic]] parish of  [[Dromcollogher-Broadford]]. In the 2016 census, the resident population of Broadford village was 276, and the population of the Broadford electoral division was 960.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ED3409&Geog_Code=2AE19629177413A3E055000000000001| title = Census 2016 - SAPMAP Area - Electoral Division - Broadford | publisher = CSO | work = Census 2016 | date = 2016 | accessdate = 19 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to records, the village is relatively new, and was first recorded by [[cartographer]]s in 1837. Prior to its current name, it was known as ''\"Killaliathan\"'' or ''\"Killagholehane\"''.<ref name=\"parish\">{{cite web | title = Dromcollogher-Broadford Parish | publisher = Diocese of Limerick Heritage Project | url = http://www.limerickdioceseheritage.org/Dromcollogher/textDromcollogher.htm | accessdate = 2008-10-01}}</ref> This name derives from [[Killaliathan Church]], located 1.6 km (1 mile) to the south, a medieval church now partially ruined.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081121194511/http://www.limerickdiocese.org/parishes/dromcollogher.htm Dromcollogher / Broadford. Parish] - [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Limerick]]\n* [http://www.logainm.ie/?text=Broadford&placeID=31690 Broadford, Co. Limerick, at the Placenames Database of Ireland]\n\n[[Category:Towns and villages in County Limerick]]\n{{County Limerick}}\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Limerick}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Broadford\n|other_name             = {{pad top italic|B\u00e9al an \u00c1tha}}\n|settlement_type        = Town\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Munster]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[County Limerick]]\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|area_footnotes         = \n|area_total_km2         = \n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population_footnotes   = <ref name=\"census2016\">{{cite web|url = http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ST2016&Geog_Code=C8875475-766E-451D-8E48-5C736DDBEA94 | title = Census 2016 - SAPMAP Area - Settlements - Broadford | publisher = CSO | work = Census 2016 | date = 2016 | accessdate = 19 August 2018}}</ref>\n|population_total       = \n|population             = 276\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|timezone1              = [[West European Time|WET]] \n|utc_offset1            = +0\n|timezone1_DST          = [[Irish Standard Time|IST]] ([[Western European Summer Time|WEST]]) \n|utc_offset1_DST        = -1\n|coordinates            = {{coord|52.3450991|-8.9740563|dim:100000_region:IE|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|elevation_m            = \n|blank_name             = [[Irish grid reference system|Irish Grid Reference]]\n|blank_info             = {{iem4ibx|R350220}}\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Broadford''' ({{Irish place name|\u00c1th Leathan}} - \"Wide Ford\") is located in the west of [[County Limerick]] in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It is part of the [[Roman Catholic]] parish of  [[Dromcollogher-Broadford]]. In the 2016 census, the resident population of Broadford village was 276, and the population of the Broadford electoral division was 960.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ED3409&Geog_Code=2AE19629177413A3E055000000000001| title = Census 2016 - SAPMAP Area - Electoral Division - Broadford | publisher = CSO | work = Census 2016 | date = 2016 | accessdate = 19 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to records, the village is relatively new, and was first recorded by [[cartographer]]s in 1837. Prior to its current name, it was known as ''\"Killaliathan\"'' or ''\"Killagholehane\"''.<ref name=\"parish\">{{cite web | title = Dromcollogher-Broadford Parish | publisher = Diocese of Limerick Heritage Project | url = http://www.limerickdioceseheritage.org/Dromcollogher/textDromcollogher.htm | accessdate = 2008-10-01}}</ref> This name derives from [[Killaliathan Church]], located 1.6 km (1 mile) to the south, a medieval church now partially ruined.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081121194511/http://www.limerickdiocese.org/parishes/dromcollogher.htm Dromcollogher / Broadford. Parish] - [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Limerick]]\n* [http://www.logainm.ie/?text=Broadford&placeID=31690 Broadford, Co. Limerick, at the Placenames Database of Ireland]\n\n[[Category:Towns and villages in County Limerick]]\n{{County Limerick}}\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Limerick}}\n", "name_user": "2001:bb6:96cf:958:ed5d:afa:c68c:538c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broadford,_County_Limerick"}
{"title_page": "Neil Trezise", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Neil Trezise\n| image = \n| birth_date = 8 February 1931\n| birth_place = [[Ballarat, Victoria]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2006|8|20|1931|2|8|df=yes}}\n| death_place = \n| originalteam = [[Redan Football Club|Redan]]\n| debutdate = 16 July 1949\n| debutteam = [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]]\n| debutopponent = [[Footscray Football Club|Footscray]]\n| debutstadium = [[Kardinia Park (stadium)|Kardinia Park]]\n| height = <!-- ### cm -->\n| weight = <!-- ### kg -->\n| position = \n| statsend = 1959\n| years1 = 1949\u20131959\n| club1 = [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]]\n| games_goals1 = 185 (272)\n| coachyears1 = 1963\n| coachclub1 = [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]]\n| coachgames_wins1 = 1 (0\u20131\u20130)\n| careerhighlights = *Geelong premiership sides 1951, 1952\n}}\n\n'''Neil Benjamin \"Nipper\" Trezise''' (8 February 1931 \u2013 20 August 2006) was an [[Australian rules football]]er who represented {{AFL Gee}} in the [[Australian Football League|Victorian Football League]] and later a politician who represented the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]] in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]]. He was of [[Cornish people|Cornish]] descent.<ref>Payton, Philip, Making Moonta: The Invention of Australia's Little Cornwall</ref>\n\n==Football career==\nOriginally from [[Redan, Victoria]], Trezise played 185 games for 272 goals between 1949 and 1959 at the [[Geelong Football Club]] in the [[Australian Football League|VFL]], playing in the 1951 and 1952 [[AFL Grand Final|premiership side]]s.<ref>[http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/N/Neil_Trezise.html Neil Trezise], ''AFL Tables''.</ref> Following his retirement in 1959 (a year in which he was Geelong captain), Trezise continued his service to the club, coaching the reserves side and then becoming club president in 1974.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/neil-trezise-was-a-champ/story-e6frf9lo-1111112161194 Neil Trezise was a champ], ''Herald Sun'', 22 August 2006.</ref>\n\nCommonly called \"Nipper\", Trezise acquired the nickname as a young recruit at Geelong.<ref name=\"The Age\">{{cite news|last=Strong|first=Geoff|title=Nipper farewelled at his old 'church'|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/nipper-farewelled-at-his-old-church/2006/08/24/1156012674178.html?from=rss|accessdate=19 July 2011|newspaper=The Age|date=25 August 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nAfter leaving football, Trezise pursued a political career with the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]]. He stood unsuccessfully for the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] [[Electoral district of Geelong|seat of Geelong]] in 1961, but won the seat of [[Electoral district of Geelong West|Geelong West]] in 1964, and held the seat and its subsequent successor [[Electoral district of Geelong North|Geelong North]] until 1992. In 1982 he became Minister for Youth, Sport and Recreation (from 1985 just Minister for Sport and Recreation), a portfolio he held until 1992\u2014throughout the entire terms of [[Premiers of Victoria|Premiers]] [[John Cain II|John Cain]] and [[Joan Kirner]].<ref>[http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=1495 Trezise, Neil Benjamin], ''Re-Member'' ('Biographical Register of the Victorian Parliament).</ref>\n\nHis son, [[Ian Trezise]], also entered politics, representing [[Electoral district of Geelong|Geelong]] in the Victorian Legislative Assembly.\n\n==Death==\nTrezise died of a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] on 20 August 2006, with his funeral held on 24 August.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200608/s1719770.htm Former Vic Govt minister Trezise dies], ''ABC News Online'', 21 August 2006.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{AustralianFootball | neil+trezise/7822 }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Max Gillett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Geelong West|Geelong West]]|years=1964\u20131967}}\n{{s-non|reason=District abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-non|reason=District created}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Geelong North|Geelong North]]|years=1967\u20131992}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Peter Loney]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Dixon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister for Youth, Sport and Recreation |years=1982\u20131985}}\n{{s-non|reason=Youth portfolio abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-non|reason=Youth portfolio abolished}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister for Sport and Recreation |years=1985\u20131992}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tom Reynolds (Australian politician)|Tom Reynolds]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{1951/52 Geelong dual premiership players}}\n{{Geelong Football Club captains}}\n{{Geelong leading goalkickers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trezise, Neil}}\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Geelong Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Geelong Football Club captains]]\n[[Category:Geelong Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:Redan Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Cornish descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Geelong]]\n[[Category:Australian sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ballarat]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Neil Trezise\n| image = \n| birth_date = 8 February 1931\n| birth_place = [[Ballarat, Victoria]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2006|8|20|1931|2|8|df=yes}}\n| death_place = \n| originalteam = [[Redan Football Club|Redan]]\n| debutdate = 16 July 1949\n| debutteam = [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]]\n| debutopponent = [[Footscray Football Club|Footscray]]\n| debutstadium = [[Kardinia Park (stadium)|Kardinia Park]]\n| height = <!-- ### cm -->\n| weight = <!-- ### kg -->\n| position = \n| statsend = 1959\n| years1 = 1949\u20131959\n| club1 = [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]]\n| games_goals1 = 185 (272)\n| coachyears1 = 1963\n| coachclub1 = [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]]\n| coachgames_wins1 = 1 (0\u20131\u20130)\n| careerhighlights = *Geelong premiership sides 1951, 1952\n}}\n\n'''Neil Benjamin \"Nipper\" Trezise''' (8 February 1931 \u2013 20 August 2006) was an [[Australian rules football]]er who represented {{AFL Gee}} in the [[Australian Football League|Victorian Football League]] and later a politician who represented the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]] in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]]. He was of [[Cornish people|Cornish]] descent.<ref>Payton, Philip, Making Moonta: The Invention of Australia's Little Cornwall</ref>\n\n==Football career==\nOriginally from [[Redan, Victoria]], Trezise played 185 games for 272 goals between 1949 and 1959 at the [[Geelong Football Club]] in the [[Australian Football League|VFL]], playing in the 1951 and 1952 [[AFL Grand Final|premiership side]]s.<ref>[http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/N/Neil_Trezise.html Neil Trezise], ''AFL Tables''.</ref> Following his retirement in 1959 (a year in which he was Geelong captain), Trezise continued his service to the club, coaching the reserves side and then becoming club president in 1974.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/neil-trezise-was-a-champ/story-e6frf9lo-1111112161194 Neil Trezise was a champ], ''Herald Sun'', 22 August 2006.</ref>\n\nCommonly called \"Nipper\", Trezise acquired the nickname as a young recruit at Geelong.<ref name=\"The Age\">{{cite news|last=Strong|first=Geoff|title=Nipper farewelled at his old 'church'|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/nipper-farewelled-at-his-old-church/2006/08/24/1156012674178.html?from=rss|accessdate=19 July 2011|newspaper=The Age|date=25 August 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nAfter leaving football, Trezise pursued a political career with the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]]. He stood unsuccessfully for the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] [[Electoral district of Geelong|seat of Geelong]] in 1961, but won the seat of [[Electoral district of Geelong West|Geelong West]] in 1964, and held the seat and its subsequent successor [[Electoral district of Geelong North|Geelong North]] until 1992. In 1982 he became Minister for Youth, Sport and Recreation (from 1985 just Minister for Sport and Recreation), a portfolio he held until 1992\u2014throughout the entire terms of [[Premiers of Victoria|Premiers]] [[John Cain II|John Cain]] and [[Joan Kirner]].<ref>[http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=1495 Trezise, Neil Benjamin], ''Re-Member'' ('Biographical Register of the Victorian Parliament).</ref>\n\nHis son, [[Ian Trezise]], also entered politics, representing [[Electoral district of Geelong|Geelong]] in the Victorian Legislative Assembly.\n\n==Death==\nTrezise died of a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] on 20 August 2006, with his funeral held on 24 August.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200608/s1719770.htm Former Vic Govt minister Trezise dies], ''ABC News Online'', 21 August 2006.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{AustralianFootball | neil+trezise/7822 }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Max Gillett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Geelong West|Geelong West]]|years=1964\u20131967}}\n{{s-non|reason=District abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-non|reason=District created}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Geelong North|Geelong North]]|years=1967\u20131992}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Peter Loney]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Dixon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister for Youth, Sport and Recreation |years=1982\u20131985}}\n{{s-non|reason=Youth portfolio abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-non|reason=Youth portfolio abolished}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister for Sport and Recreation |years=1985\u20131992}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tom Reynolds (Australian politician)|Tom Reynolds]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{1951/52 Geelong dual premiership players}}\n{{Geelong Football Club captains}}\n{{Geelong leading goalkickers}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trezise, Neil}}\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Geelong Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Geelong Football Club captains]]\n[[Category:Geelong Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:Redan Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Cornish descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Geelong]]\n[[Category:Australian sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ballarat]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "date format audit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neil_Trezise"}
{"title_page": "The Script (album)", "text_new": ":''\"If You See Kay\" redirects here. Not to be confused with \"[[If U Seek Amy]]\".''\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Script\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Script]]\n| cover      = Script album.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 8 August 2008\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Alternative rock]]\n*[[pop rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 38:23\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Phonogenic Records|Phonogenic]]|[[Epic Records|Epic]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Steve Kipner]]|[[Danny O'Donoghue]]|Andrew Frampton|Mark Sheehan}}\n| prev_title = iTunes Festival: London 2008\n| prev_year  = 2008\n| next_title = iTunes Sessions\n| next_year  = 2010\n| misc         = \n{{Singles\n | name        = The Script\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[We Cry]]\n | single1date = 28 April 2008\n | single2     = [[The Man Who Can't Be Moved]]\n | single2date = 28 July 2008\n | single3     = [[Breakeven (song)|Breakeven]]\n | single3date = 24 November 2008\n | single4     = [[Talk You Down]]\n | single4date = 16 March 2009\n | single5     = [[Before the Worst]]\n | single5date = 15 June 2009\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Script''''' is the debut album by Irish [[pop rock]] band [[the Script]], which was released in the Republic of Ireland on 8 August 2008 and was released in the UK on 11 August 2008 by [[Phonogenic Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B0019MLVEM|title=The Script|publisher=}}</ref> Following success in the Republic of Ireland, the album was released elsewhere in Europe in September 2008. The album topped the UK charts and peaked at number 64 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] on 4 March 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=the script|chart=all}} |title=Billboard.com - Discography - The Script |date=4 April 2009 |accessdate=29 April 2009 |magazine=Billboard |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523083551/http://www.billboard.com/artist/419066/script/chart |archivedate=23 May 2013 }}</ref> The album was nominated for a [[Choice Music Prize]]-[[Irish Album of the Year 2008]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/5171298.html|title=Choice Music Prize Shortlist|date=14 January 2009|accessdate=16 January 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press (magazine)|Hot Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imro.ie/newstastic//news.php?item=9762 |title=Choice Music Prize - Shortlist Announced |date=15 January 2009 |accessdate=16 January 2009 |publisher=[[Irish Music Rights Organisation|IMRO]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503000228/http://www.imro.ie/newstastic//news.php?item=9670 |archivedate=3 May 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2009/0115/choicemusicprize.html|title=Choice Music nominees announced|date=15 January 2009|accessdate=16 January 2009|publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n| rev2      = [[BBC]]\n| rev2Score = (Positive)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/jbhj/|title=BBC - Music - Review of The Script - The Script|publisher=}}</ref>\n| rev3      = [[Digital Spy]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Digital Spy review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/amusic/a122052/the-script-the-script.html|title=The Script: 'The Script'|author=Nick Levine|date=12 August 2008|work=Digital Spy}}</ref>\n| rev4      = [[Entertainment.ie]]\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.ie/album-review/The-Script---The-Script/5797.htm|title=Music Review - The Script - The Script - entertainment.ie|work=entertainment.ie}}</ref>\n| rev5      = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/aug/08/popreview.thescript|title=CD: Pop review: The Script, The Script|author=John Burgess|newspaper=the Guardian|date=7 August 2008}}</ref>\n| rev6      = [[MTV Asia]]\n| rev6Score = (7/10)<ref>[http://www.mtvasia.com/Review/CD/C20080901001700.html MTV Asia review] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227055409/http://www.mtvasia.com/Review/CD/C20080901001700.html |date=27 December 2008 }}</ref>\n| rev7      = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev7Score = (2/10){{citation needed|date=January 2012}}\n| rev8      = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-the-script-the-script-rca-904927.html|title=Album: The Script, The Script (RCA)|author=Andy Gill|date=21 August 2008|work=The Independent}}</ref>\n| rev9      = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/cd_reviews/article4464986.ece|title=Login|work=The Times}}</ref>\n}}\nThe album was met with mixed reviews by music critics. Timothy Powell of the ''[[BBC]]'' stated that the album \"reveals a band that is fresh, vital and ferociously good.\" He went on to say that the Script are now positioned as \"next big thing\" and that the album entails \"hip-hop, pop melodiousness, state-of-the-art production and anthemic rock.\" His overall summary was that the album is \"Intelligent, beautifully crafted and compelling.\"<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/jbhj/ Rock & Indie review - The Script, ''The Script'']</ref> Nick Levine of ''[[Digital Spy]]'' gave the album 3/5 stars while saying it was often \"devastatingly effective\" and that  \"A lot of people are going to hate the Script, a lot of people are going to love the Script.\"<ref name=\"Digital Spy review\"/>\n\nThe German ''[[WOM magazin]]'' monthly went as far as writing: \"''Eigenst\u00e4nding und originell ist anders. The Script bringen die Misere der Musikindustrie auf den Punkt.'' (Independent and original [music] is different. The Script points out the music industry's demise.)\"<ref name=wom>{{cite journal|title=musik angeh\u00f6rt|journal=WOM Magazin|issue=8 September|page=23|publisher=World of Music|language=de}}</ref> The album has mixed reviews in [[MTV Asia]], which has praised \"O'Donoghue's vocals are a pleasurably unique aural experience\" though it also comments that, as a whole, \"the album plays across a flat plane, with no big leaps, but no huge letdowns either.\"<ref>[http://www.mtvasia.com/Review/CD/C20080901001700.html MTVAsia Reviews - The Script] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227055409/http://www.mtvasia.com/Review/CD/C20080901001700.html |date=27 December 2008 }}</ref> [[AllMusic]]'s Alexey Eremenko said that the album was \"not reckless or fuzzy enough [to be] power pop\"; instead the closest discernible influence was the [[rock music|rock]] style of [[U2]].<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-script-mw0000811253|title=The Script|author=Dave Donnelly|work=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\nFollowing the success of \"[[The Man Who Can't Be Moved]]\", ''The Script'' entered the UK Albums Charts at number one with sales of 54,520 copies where it stayed for two weeks. The album spent eight weeks in the top ten and was the twelfth best selling album in the UK of 2008. The album also entered the [[Irish Album Chart]] at number one, holding the top spot for five weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/album/37191 |title=The Script - The Script - Music Charts |publisher=Acharts.us |date= |accessdate=21 September 2010}}</ref> It had, of January 2009, spent twenty two weeks in the top ten. The Irish office of Sony BMG music presented the group with their first multi-Platinum award disc for over 600,000 sales of ''The Script''. On Sunday, 18 January 2009, the album went back up to number 1 in the UK Album Charts, a whole 5 months since it was first released, mainly because of the \u00a33.95 deal on [[iTunes]]. Though released in 2008, the album was the 198th best-selling album in 2010 in the USA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2010/the-billboard-200?begin=181&order=position|title=Billboard}}</ref> It has so far spent over 174 weeks in the UK albums chart.\n\n===Singles===\nFive singles were released from ''The Script''. The first single that released from the album was \"[[We Cry]]\". The song peaked at #13 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. It was followed by the second single, \"[[The Man Who Can't Be Moved]]\", which peaked at number 2 on the UK Singles Chart, becoming the Script's highest charting single. In December 2008, the Script released \"[[Breakeven (song)|Breakeven]]\" as their third single from the album. It peaked at number 21 on the UK chart. The Script then released \"[[Talk You Down]]\" in 2009, as the fourth single from the album. However, the single failed to reach the success of the album's first three singles, missing the UK Top 40 and only peaking at number 47. \"Breakeven\" was released in fall 2009 in the United States and the Script performed it live on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' on 14 October 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetunemusic.com/2009/10/video-script-breakeven-live-on-ellen.html |accessdate=15 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022081910/http://www.thetunemusic.com/2009/10/video-script-breakeven-live-on-ellen.html |archivedate=22 October 2009 }}</ref> \"Breakeven\" then went on to peak at 12 in the US where it was also certified Platinum for shipment of 1,000,000 copies. \"Breakeven\" was also released in Australia where it peaked at number 3 and was certified Platinum.\n\nIn May 2009, the Script confirmed that a fifth single would be released from the album. \"[[Before the Worst]]\" was released on 15 June 2009 in the UK. It peaked at number 96 on the UK Singles Chart, becoming the lowest charting single from ''The Script'' in the UK. \"Before the Worst\" was also released in Australia where it peaked at number 10 and has been certified Gold.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1          = [[We Cry]]\n| length1         = 3:45\n| writer1         = Andrew Frampton, [[Danny O'Donoghue]], Glen Power, [[Mark Sheehan]], [[Steve Kipner]]\n| extra1          = Frampton, Kipner\n| title2          = [[Before the Worst]]\n| length2         = 3:23\n| writer2         = O'Donoghue, Power, Sheehan\n| extra2          = Frampton, Kipner\n| title3          = [[Talk You Down]]\n| length3         = 3:51\n| writer3         = O'Donoghue, Sheehan\n| extra3          = Sheehan\n| title4          = [[The Man Who Can't Be Moved]]\n| length4         = 4:02\n| writer4         = Frampton, O'Donoghue, Sheehan, Kipner\n| extra4          = Frampton, Kipner\n| title5          = [[Breakeven (song)|Breakeven]]\n| length5         = 4:21\n| writer5         = Frampton, O'Donoghue, Sheehan, Kipner\n| extra5          = Frampton, Kipner\n| title6          = Rusty Halo\n| length6         = 3:35\n| writer6         = O'Donoghue, Sheehan\n| extra6          = Sheehan\n| title7          = The End Where I Begin\n| length7         = 3:34\n| writer7         = O'Donoghue, Sheehan\n| extra7          = Sheehan\n| title8          = Fall for Anything\n| length8         = 4:33\n| writer8         = O'Donoghue, Sheehan\n| extra8          = Sheehan\n| title9          = If You See Kay\n| length9         = 3:14\n| writer9         = O'Donoghue, Sheehan, Tony McGuinness\n| extra9          = Sheehan\n| title10         = I'm Yours\n| length10        = 4:15\n| writer10        = O'Donoghue\n| extra10         = Sheehan\n| total_length = 38:23\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| headline        = Bonus track<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.livrariacultura.com.br/scripts/musica/resenha/resenha.asp?nitem=11029430&sid=2051661091298293541897653&k5=2B7B8B78&uid= |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120630154628/http://www.livrariacultura.com.br/scripts/musica/resenha/resenha.asp?nitem=11029430&sid=2051661091298293541897653&k5=2B7B8B78&uid= |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 June 2012 |title=Cd: Script, The - The Script - R&B & Soul |publisher=Livrariacultura.com.br |accessdate=21 September 2010 }}</ref>\n| title11         = Anybody There\n| writer11        = O'Donoghue, Sheehan\n| extra11         = Sheehan\n| length11        = 3:00\n| total_length = 41:23\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| headline        = Japanese bonus tracks<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdjapan.co.jp/detailview.html?KEY=BVCP-25151 |title=The Script The Script [CD&#93; |publisher=Cdjapan.co.jp |date=22 October 2008 |accessdate=21 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thescriptmusic.com/jp/music/releases/el/ |title=The Script &#124; Music |publisher=Thescriptmusic.com |accessdate=21 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725132810/http://www.thescriptmusic.com/jp/music/releases/el/ |archivedate=25 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| title11         = Anybody There\n| writer11        = O'Donoghue, Sheehan\n| extra11         = Sheehan\n| length11        = 3:00\n| title12         = [[Live Like We're Dying]]\n| writer12        = O'Donoghue, Sheehan, Frampton, Kipner\n| extra12         = Frampton, Kipner\n| length12        = 3:34\n| title13         = We Cry\n| writer13        = O'Donoghue, Sheehan, Power, Frampton, Kipner\n| extra13         = Frampton, Kipner\n| note13          = Live Mix\n| length13        = 4:16\n| total_length = 49:13\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Deluxe edition bonus DVD<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=460597 |title = The Script the Script Japanese 2-disc CD/DVD set (460597)}}</ref>\n| title1  = We Cry\n| note1   = Music Video\n| length